eventName: Nottingham Office Charity Social: The Great Debate - Coffee Vote!!!
story:
When naming  Coffee with Colleagues, few realised how polarising the name would become!

So after roughly 3 years since it's inception, it's time to answer the question once and for all : What is the Nottingham Office's favourite hot drink? Tea? Coffee? Other!?

Wars have been fought over less divisive questions, but we're hoping by holding this event, we can settle the debate for good (oh, we should have mentioned that this is all for charity)!

 The Social Bit

The Great Debate will be an hour long, and run via Teams. Over the hour, we will be randomly breaking people out into 10 minute calls with 2 or 3 other people from the office. In these mini-breakout calls, you can chat about whatever you want - but just keep in mind that after 10 minutes, you will automatically return to the main call!

After each 10 minute breakout chat, there will be around 5 minutes of down time to avoid it from getting too hectic.

 The Charity Bit

To decide on a winning beverage, attendees will need to vote via charity donations. There are 3 charities, each one representing a different option.

Your vote for coffee will help raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support.

Macmillan Cancer Support provides specialist health care, information and financial support to people affected by cancer. It also looks at the social, emotional and practical impact cancer can have, and campaigns for better cancer care. Macmillan Cancer Support's goal is to reach and improve the lives of everyone who has cancer in the UK.
https://www.macmillan.org.uk/

pageSummaryWhat: For those wishing to donate in memory of Tony
pageSummaryWhy: of the incredible work they do for so many
story:
Tony/Dad was diagnosed with Mesothelioma late last year, a cancer brought on by exposure to asbestos. Despite trying chemotherapy and Immunotherapy, we all knew these treatments were only ever going to be palliative and not a cure. However, we never imagined that his life would end so suddenly and without warning. It was his wish to have donations made to Macmillan Cancer Support in his memory to ensure all cancer sufferers are able to benefit from the amazing work that Macmillan do. Due to covid 19 restrictions, so many were unable to attend his funeral and therefore the family has set up this just giving page to allow you to donate to Macmillan in his memory.

Thank you

pageSummaryWhat: I am walking 10,000 steps a day in March
story:
Macmillan cancer support do such a amazing job and have supported many people I know, in many different ways 

This March I am walking 10,000 steps a day to raise money for this amazing charity, they are not just there for cancer patients but also there to support people when a family member is at end of life care, I lost my grandad this year to something that wasn’t cancer but Macmillan palliative care support were there for my family when he was in his last days, he was my best friend, hero, one in a million, and I want to walk 10,000 steps for him this March, 

I also want to walk for my grandma this year who lost her battle to cancer in 2013, Macmillan cancer support were there to support us all through this horrible time too, 

I know so many people who have cancer, Beaten this horrible disease, and Sadly people who have passed away and Macmillan have/ do a amazing job to support each and everyone of this people,  

Thank you so much for everyone’s support

eventName: Edd, Joe and Friends run/walk 2500km in March
story:
We would like to thank you so much for visiting our just giving page and for any donations you have or are about to give. 

As some of you may or may not have heard, the funniest, most loving and generous man in our lives has passed away. Graham Williams (Taid) was the epicentre of our small family, and was someone who brought smiles and joy to everyone he met. No matter where we went, whether just to the cricket or to a fancy restaurant he would stand and talk to complete strangers and bring a smile to their face with a little joke or just his kind hearted nature. He was unquestionably liked and loved by everyone who knew him whether it was for a day, a year or a lifetime in our case. 

The past year has been a difficult one for many people with COVID and for us as a family it has been the cruelest of circumstances with restrictions keeping us apart with such little time to spare with our Taid. Towards the end we got to spend a little time with him and he bravely fought his fight with Cancer right to the end. 

The care he got from Macmillan and other Nurses throughout the last few weeks of his life was truly exceptional. They were there to help him at all hours of the day and through the night and my grandma was very thankful for their wonderful support. 

SO to the Fundraising!! 

In memory of our Taid and as a thank you to Macmillan for the brilliant work they do we decided to try to do some fundraising by running/walking a certain distance in March. After speaking to a couple of friends about it, within an hour we had 13 other of our friends and family wanting to join us and help raise money. It really was heartwarming to get that support from our mates without any hesitation. 

Our team of 15 family and friends are going to run/walk 2500km in 31 days of March. This is the distance of a marathon every week EACH (41km)!!! We will be tracking all of our distance as a team on the Strava app and uploading our progress on a regular basis for you all to see how were getting on! All donations will go directly to Macmillan Cancer Support so please give generously!

Again, on behalf of our family we would like to thank all the boys for helping us, to Macmillan for their support and to all of you for your donations! 

We love you millions and miss you Taid xx

OUR 2500KM TEAM: 

Edd Williams-Gray, Joe Williams-Gray, Karlton Gray, Tom Geeson, Brad Farrell, Andy Welden, Matt Welden, Sam Pritchard, Morgan Robinson, Harrison Holmes, Harvey Holmes, Rhodri Mayor, Ash Jones, Lewis Barker and Ben Stavely.

Hi guys. MK has decided to dedicate one night per week to making different cakes/desserts and selling these for charity (very proud mum moment). She has decided to donate this money to Macmillan throughout March, starting Saturday 27th February. As her mum, I will oversee this and ensure everything is done correctly. We are on the food register to trade from our home address and I have my level 2 food hygiene. I will provide her with enough packaging for the month, the ingredients for her 1st week and deliver everyone's orders with her. Ingredients for the remaining weeks will be taken from the money she makes and the rest will go directly to Macmillan. She will choose a few different items to sell each week and you can choose from these. There will be hot and cold options available each week and Vanilla ice cream as an optional extra. These will be made up on Saturday afternoons and delivered between 6 and 8pm on Saturday evenings. A post will be put up at the beginning of each week with 'whats on the menu' so you can get your order in before the Saturday.

pageSummary: We are raising money and awareness because we don’t want cancer to be the forgotten C word
pageSummaryWhat: We are raising money and awareness
pageSummaryWhy: we don’t want cancer to be the forgotten C word
story:
Unfortunately, one C word is stopping us from holding our charity netball tournament for yet another year so we’re mixing things up to do our bit for the other C word!

In March last year, we very quickly had to hang our netball trainers up and stay at home as the world navigated its way through a global pandemic. Whilst this is far from over and we can’t be certain about the future of our beloved sport and when we’ll be back on that court shouting ‘here if you need’, we can be certain that we can still make a difference and help those in need off court. 

Whilst some of us have quickly adapted to new ways of exercising (kudos to you guys), some of us took the opportunity to sit on the sofa watching Netflix and eating cake so we’ve set ourselves a challenge that some will find harder than others but let’s face it, you’re only as strong as your weakest link so we’d like to think our challenge is achievable by all!

On Sunday 25th April 2021, the day we would usually hold the tournament, together as a netball club we will be running, walking, cycling or moving in whichever way one desires 5 miles each. Please support us in whatever way you can and even better, join us if you like! 

Let’s help to stop cancer becoming the forgotten C in the coronavirus pandemic.

story:
My auntie Donna  was a loving Mother, Daughter, Sister, Wife, Aunt, Nan and friend to many people who loved her dearly. She was known for her fantastic baking skills (Cornish pasties being her specialty!) and was always the life of the party (especially once she’d had a couple of glasses of wine haha!) Some of my favourite childhood memories took place at Donna’s house, we could stay up late, watch movies and we certainly never went without a midnight feast!

Shortly after celebrating her 50th birthday, Donna was taken into hospital after feeling really poorly and after many blood transfusions and tests, we found out that Donna had a rare form of blood cancer called Myelofibrosis. She spent the later months staying incredibly strong and positive but unfortunately on 31/10/2017 - Auntie Donna lost her battle and sadly passed away.   

Macmillan is an incredible charity who help countless families who are battling cancer and they rely heavily on fundraising to be able to continue to do that. Most families have either been effected or know someone who has been effected by cancer. 

At the end of July I’ll be taking part in the great hike- Dedham Vale in Auntie Donna’s memory. This is a 26 mile hike which will be the furthest I’ve walked, I’ll be training for this in the meantime to ensure I can complete it! I’m aware that this is a really hard time financially for a lot of people with everything that’s happened in the world, however if there’s anything you can spare, every pound will take me a step closer to my goal.


Thanks for reading.


Brooke x

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
You go to the village fete and choke on your Mr Whippy. Who's there? St John. You ask someone to come and do a talk to the village about how to use a defibrillator. Who rocks up? St John. You fall into a ditch at mile 21 of a marathon. Who scoops you up and listens to you rambling? St John. There's a worldwide pandemic and an army of volunteers is deployed to help the NHS. Who are they? Of course.

St John are the unsung heroes lurking at events, races, vaccination centres. They are cool, calm and ready to take on whatever duties are required of them.

I decided to join them in a small way as a Vaccination Care Volunteer and in doing so realised just how much they do in the community and how much of a pickle we'd be in without them.

 I know I've run one or two marathons in my time so this may not seem like a challenge but I will balance training with full-time work and shifts as a volunteer on the side. If my fragile legs can take a bit of punishment, I may attempt that elusive PB that I haven't managed for 7 long years so this won't be a walk in the park. It will be a Marathon on the streets of Brighton.


Thanks for reading and thanks for your donation :)

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: Chris`s Skydive for British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation, a charity that is very special to me and my family and I will be doing it from 10,000 ft. Doing a skydive has been on my bucket list for a couple years now, so I thought what better way of raising money than jumping out a plane and getting the rush of free falling at 120mph, I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK, but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target, and get the chance to watch me jump out a plane from 10,000 ft, Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Kier Group has selected the British Heart Foundation, the biggest independent funder of cardiovascular research in the UK, as its new corporate charity partner. The two-year partnership will help in the charitys aim of increasing awareness of cardiovascular disease, raise £250,000 for vital research in to heart and circulatory conditions as well as train 1,500 Kier colleagues in the lifesaving first aid, CPR.

The British Heart Foundation is funding life saving research to help end heartbreak for the seven million people in the UK living with cardiovascular disease. For over 50 years it has pioneered research that has transformed the lives of people living with heart and circulatory conditions and has been pivotal to offering vital treatments that are changing the fight against heart disease.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As a family we would like to raise as much money as possible for the British Heart Foundation. 

We want to do this jump in August but it could be pushed to a later date because of lock down but once we have a definite date it will be posted. I thank you for your patience on this part. So far there are 8 of us jumping but this could increase.

It is a Charity close to our hearts as we lost our nephew due to a heart defect he would have been 30 last December, we would also like to raise as much money as possible to aid the valuable research that is needed to help us all remain healthy. 

We have chosen a tandem parachute jump for this Charity as we are all petrified of heights lol so wish us luck they will have to chuck me out of the plane. 

Thank you so much for taking the time to read this and please donate 🙏 and hopefully we can all help to save lives x

pageSummaryWhat: Emily is going to do fun activities to raise money
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation by Emily doing some activities that are good for her wellbeing.  I will make  donations for these activities in memory of my father John, and Emily's Grandfather known as Pappa. 

Pappa was a wonderful man who loved the great outdoors, particularly nature and the natural surroundings. A very sporty man who in his early days was a talented Cricketer, Tennis Player, Golfer and Sailor. He also loved travelling, particularly in Africa where he went on many adventures and safaris.

Pappa sadly passed away from heart disease in his mid seventies. If we can help raise awareness and support research by donating to this charity then hopefully more lives will be saved and other sufferers of heart disease will get the help need  to elongate their lives.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thomas and I love our chocolate so we have decided to give it up for all of March and raise some money for this great cause. 


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I am giving up choclate,sweets,fizz,cake and booze because Of  my husband  and In memory of my grandad
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up choclate,sweets,fizz,cake and booze
pageSummaryWhy: Of  my husband  and In memory of my grandad
story:
This is my second year taking part in Dechox. I have a family history of heart related conditions and have  seen first  through personal and work what strokes can do to not only the individuals but their families .  Only recently my OH was rushed to hospital with a suspected bleed on the brain due to blood pressure.  Due to comorbis conditions he is at extremely high risk of a stroke or other heart conditions. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: Spare the price of a Freddo because You’ll know someone affected by heart disease
pageSummaryWhat: Spare the price of a Freddo
pageSummaryWhy: You’ll know someone affected by heart disease
story:
Giving up chocolate for March because since I’ve been able to eat dairy I’ve scoffed about a year’s worth of chocolate in 2 weeks.  Seen this Dechox come up on my timeline and thought might as well start again in March for bit and see if anyone will give me the price of a Freddo or four to donate to BHF. 


The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Times are hard & we all want to help where we can so me giving up chocolate, sweets & fizzy drinks for March isn't really too much to ask....I hope!

If you could just donate a little towards my little challenge then that would be lovely for me and for others... See the following message from BHF:

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate for a month because My Auntie Helena had to have open heart surgery
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate for a month
pageSummaryWhy: My Auntie Helena had to have open heart surgery
story:
I am giving up chocolate for a month because My Auntie Helena had to have open heart surgery last year and I was really sad & worried about her ❤️❤️

As most people know I do not eat any type of sweeties but I LOVE chocolate 😍

For me to give up chocolate for 31 days means no snack at school 😩no treats at the weekend 😩😩......... but I will hopefully with your help raise some money for British heart foundation 😀😀😀 and enjoy Easter eggs at the end of the challenge 🍫🍫🍫

Thank you to everyone taking the time to read this & hopefully sponsor me 🤞🏻🤞🏻

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story:
As some of you may know my Dad was taken poorly last year with his heart. Thankfully he is now doing great. The British Heart Foundation is a fantastic charity. Due to the pandemic raising money has been very difficult for everyone. So I plan to give up chocolate for the month of March..Yes a whole month!! This for me will be very difficult but I WILL do it.

Please donate if you can, THANK YOU xxx

pageSummary: I am giving up sweet treats because I hate myself. Also to raise money. :)
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up sweet treats
pageSummaryWhy: I hate myself. Also to raise money. :)
story:
Hi everyone!

As you can see, I have decided to give up chocolate for the month of March. Because I am clearly a masochist, I have chosen to take on the toughest of the three available challenges and also give up sweets and fizzy drinks. 

Many of you are probably aware that I don't and never have consumed fizzy drinks. I'm also not a huge sweet eater in the grand scheme of things. So, to make sure that this challenge is actually a -challenge-, I will personally be giving up chocolate (my favourite food), cake (I'm a keen baker and March is my birthday month), and ice cream (my other favourite food), including ice cream derivatives like milkshakes.

Why have I decided to torture myself so thoroughly? Well, because this is important. Despite them being the world's biggest killers, heart and circulatory diseases only get a fraction of the funding of other killers like cancer. This is not to say that research into these other illnesses doesn't deserve the funding they get, because of course they do. But it is to say that more can be done and needs to be done to help people with heart issues.

To make this a bit more fun, I'm planning to keep everybody regularly updated on my slow journey into sugar-deprived insanity via blog posts or Instagram posts or similar. I'm still working out that part, but I'll be sure to update everybody as and when I decide how I'll be keeping you all entertained. 

For now, I invite you to read on and find out how the BHF has been coping with fundraising efforts during the pandemic. Thank you for taking the time to read what I have to say, and please do donate if you've got a couple of quid to spare.

All the best,
Gillian

--

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because, despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
So here it goes........a month of no chocolate and sweets. I'm not going to lie but this is going to be so difficult for me, especially as I tend to eat chocolate when stressed, happy, sad, bored and pretty much any other emotions there is 😂 

However on a serious note, I want to do this in order to stop bad habits as well as to make sure this heart of mine stays healthy as it still has so much love to give 🤗

Despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. I am doing this to encourage my family and friends to be the healthiest versions of themselves so we all can have many more years together ❤

Would be great to have a few donations to this good cause as well as having anyone join me.

Sending you all lots of love ❤❤

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I am raising money because they need our support more than ever!
pageSummaryWhy: they need our support more than ever!
story: At the end of last year I decided to give up chocolate, crisps and cakes for 3 months allowing myself to only have a few days where I can 'cheat' including my 30th birthday ( as I have to eat cake then?!) I then came along this choc-detox for British heart foundation and thought what a great cause to try and raise some money for! The company I work for will double any money raised, I know this last year has been hard for everyone but it is important we will raise money for research to be done for other causes as they have all taken a big hit! Please donate as little or much as you can ! Nearly 2 months in, in a lockdown, not allowed any chocolate crisps or cake, I have been told I'm mad!

pageSummary: I am going chocolate free in March because of my gorgeous goddaughter Bronwyn 😍
pageSummaryWhat: I am going chocolate free in March
story:
Born with a heart murmur, my gorgeous goddaughter, Bronwyn, underwent open heart surgery at just 8 months old. Thanks to the research and work of the British Heart Foundation and the amazing surgeons, the surgery was a success and Bronwyn is now six years old. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge The Heart Foundation have faced in their 60 year history. It's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help The British Heart Foundation keep up the pace of progress. Despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. 

Please support if you can 😊

Thank you 😘

pageSummary: I am hoping to raise money because it's a charity that is personal to me.
pageSummaryWhat: I am hoping to raise money
pageSummaryWhy: it's a charity that is personal to me.
story:
My dad had a heart attack and needed surgery some years back, it was a scary time. The care he received and the surgery gave him more years of his life and when he was taken from us with cancer, until the very last moments his heart was beating so strong we could almost hear it!! To raise money for the British Heart Foundation, I will be giving up chocolate and sweets for the whole of March (something that those of you who know me well will appreciate will NOT be an easy feat!!). Any donation, no matter how modest, will be greatly appreciated. Thank you.

pageSummary: I’m raising money for because It’s very close to my heart ❤️
pageSummaryWhy: It’s very close to my heart ❤️
story:
I’m doing this years de-choc in memory of my precious Dad ♥️ Dad passed away suddenly at just 62 years of age in March 2020. I want to raise money so I can donate to BHF in my dads name to help them continue their life saving support and research,  and hopefully avoid even one person passing away.  Please only donate if you feel able to.  I understand how hard a time it is for lots of people just now.   I miss & love my Dad ♥️ so very much but the least I can do is give up my favourite thing (chocolate 😋) to help others 

In memory of you Dad ♥️ Love you all the way to the moon & back.  Your ghirl Clare xx

pageSummary: So I'm giving up the choc for a month! because I'm looking after my heart and getting fitter.
pageSummaryWhat: So I'm giving up the choc for a month!
pageSummaryWhy: I'm looking after my heart and getting fitter.
story:
Hitting the big 50 and being rather over weight had given me food for thought. Quite literally.  

We have heart conditions in our genes and even my mum suffered a massive heart attack a few years ago.   I'm never going to be a Saint but I do need a kick start back to fitness and why not raise some much needed funds for a worthwhile and much needed charity.  

For 31 days I will not eat chocolates or sweets or cakes or biscuits. ( oh I'm going to die). I'm also going to make sure I walk at least 10 miles a week with my dogs. 

Please help me out guys.. It all starts on the 1st march, so I can eat all my birthday treats, and ends on 31st march.  Let's do this xxxx

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks because I suffered from pregnancy induced hypertension
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks
pageSummaryWhy: I suffered from pregnancy induced hypertension
story:
Just over 4 years ago on my son's due date I was diagnosed with Pregnancy Induced Hypertension. My blood pressure shot up so quickly my husband was told I was close to having a stroke. 

During my second pregnancy in 2019/20 I was considered high risk and had to take daily aspirin. Once again my blood pressure shot up in labour and after birth. This time however, just weeks before the first lockdown, I was lucky enough to be part of a research study allowing me to be monitored remotely using a smart cuff and an app. This allowed my cardiologist to change my medication quickly and easily. Even so it took 6 months for my body to recover. 

Even since then the advice has changed for women with Pregnancy Induced Hypertension and I'm incredibly grateful for the opportunity the study gave me to stay safely at home and not endure an even longer hospital stay. 

Anyone who knows me will know that with two young children, chocolate is my weakness and my crutch. A sugar boost to get me through the day. A bag of Twirl bites, a quick teaspoon of Nutella... Oooh I'm going to miss Nutella crumpets. 

I always say that if someone is doing something for charity it should be something that's hard for them and this will be really hard!! 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I’m taking part in memory of Aunty Eileen because she was my 2nd mum and had a heart attack in 2007
pageSummaryWhat: I’m taking part in memory of Aunty Eileen
pageSummaryWhy: she was my 2nd mum and had a heart attack in 2007
story:
After losing 2 stone last year I’ve realised that I still haven’t cured my sugar addiction. Not many people realise that this is a serious form of addiction and can affect your health massively. 

I lost my Aunty Eileen in 2007 when she had a heart attack, I miss her every single day and she was my 2nd mum. 

My mum who had Alzheimer’s also had vascular dementia and passed in 2014 

My sister Meryl had a stroke in 2018 and has had to give up work 

So I have many reasons to do this so please help me to be accountable by donating

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate for 1 month because This is an important charity to my family
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate for 1 month
pageSummaryWhy: This is an important charity to my family
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge the British Heart Foundation  has faced in their 60 year history and it's led to them  being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So I have decided to do my bit by doing this Virtual fundraising challenge,  Dechox, giving up chocolate and fizzy drinks for the 31 days of March. 

It is going to take a lot of willpower as anyone who knows me knows I have a huge chocolate addiction but I am determined to do it and hopefully friends and family will support me, help me reach my target,  to help raise some money for further research. 

Why am I doing it? My husband and both his brothers have had heart surgery so it it personal to my family. 

Any money raised will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need it most, because, despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still out there and kill.

pageSummary: Chocoholic Dechox Challenge because Everyone deserves good health 💜
story:
Do you want to help in a good cause supporting the British Heart Foundation in life saving research? If yes, then read on! 

Chocoholics unite! Give up chocolate, or more, for 31 days in March to raise money for life saving research and be part of a movement to beat heartbreak forever. Every pound you raise will help fund vital research into heart and circulatory diseases with the British Heart Foundation ❤ 


My middle name should be chocoholic, I indulge in that much of the tasty stuff. And if I can curb the appetite thru a Dechox to raise awareness and support lifesaving research for 31 days throughout March, then I'll give it my best shot.

Thank you for your support. 

Much love 💜

Dechox 2021

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hi all ❤️  From now till March, I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation as part of the collective effort to drive change for people affected by heart and circulatory diseases. 

Heart and circulatory diseases cause more than a quarter of all deaths in the UK every year- that's 160,000 deaths each year- or one death every three minutes. 

60 years ago, the number of deaths due to heart diseases was twice today's figure; Since the British Heart Foundation was established, the number of deaths attributed to heart & circulatory diseases has fallen by more than half. 

This has only been made possible because of the £100 million of research each year that's been funded by the British Heart Foundation into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them.

The impact of Covid 19, however, has cut their research budget by half. In such a difficult year, let's join forces and raise money for research, to make sure we have more time with the people we love ❤️ 

Today, there might still be no cure for heart failure, neither can we save every child born with congenital heart disease, or give every stroke victim the best chance of recovery. But every dollar counts and that's why in the month of March, I'm participating in Dechox and giving up on chocolates for 31 days to raise money for research. Join me and be a part of this movement to beat heartbreak forever x

pageSummary: I am Dechoxing and giving Sweets the push because They need vital support now more than ever
pageSummaryWhat: I am Dechoxing and giving Sweets the push
pageSummaryWhy: They need vital support now more than ever
story:
Having Heart disease from birth, born with Transposition of the Greater Arteries, numerous operations, a Balloon fitted at 9 yrs old & a stent fitted at 14 yrs old in the Heart 

26th of February 2011 I suffered a Cardiac Arrest, which I have a Pacemaker and ICD in place. 

10 yrs since that day and what better way of saying thanks and helping vital research into our biggest killer. 

Because the pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in the BHF 60 year history. The British Heart Foundation needs people like you and me more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Please join me either way..... We NEED to look after our HEARTS 

OUR HEALTH IS OUR WEALTH

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate for whole of March 2021 because It is an important charity to my family
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate for whole of March 2021
pageSummaryWhy: It is an important charity to my family
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge the British Heart Foundation has faced in their 60 year history and it's led to them being forced to make the devastating decision to cut their 2020 research budget in half. So I have decided to join this virtual fundraising challenge - Dechox - I will be giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy drinks for the 31 days of March. 

It is going to take a lot of willpower, as anyone who knows me knows I am a chocoholic but I am determined to do it and hopefully friends and family will support me to reach my target. 

Why am I doing it? because my husband and both his brothers have had heart surgery so it is personal to my family.

All donations will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need it most because, despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers.

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.

It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. 

By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

eventName: The Great Debate - Nottingham Office Charity Social
story:
When naming  Coffee with Colleagues, few realised how polarising the name would become!

So after roughly 3 years since it's inception, it's time to answer the question once and for all : What is the Nottingham Office's favourite hot drink? Tea? Coffee? Other!?

Wars have been fought over less divisive questions, but we're hoping by holding this event, we can settle the debate for good (oh, we should have mentioned that this is all for charity)!

 The Social Bit

The Great Debate will be an hour long, and run via Teams. Over the hour, we will be randomly breaking people out into 10 minute calls with 2 or 3 other people from the office. In these mini-breakout calls, you can chat about whatever you want - but just keep in mind that after 10 minutes, you will automatically return to the main call!

After each 10 minute breakout chat, there will be around 5 minutes of down time to avoid it from getting too hectic.

 The Charity Bit

To decide on a winning beverage, attendees will need to vote via charity donations. There are 3 charities, each one representing a different option.

Your vote for Tea will help raise money for Guide Dogs 


Guide Dogs provides a wide range of services for children and young people, including mobility and life skills, large print books and grants for specialist technology. And we're here for the whole family, providing support and advice on a range of issues, including education.
https://www.guidedogs.org.uk/

pageSummary: Remembering my Mum Sandra Warde and raising money because she loved dogs and proud of her dad who went blind
pageSummaryWhat: Remembering my Mum Sandra Warde and raising money
pageSummaryWhy: she loved dogs and proud of her dad who went blind
story:
As we are unable to take physical collections at the cremation, we wanted to still remember my mum Sandra through combining her love for dogs (we all know a story or two) with her immense pride for her father Alex who went blind and re trained to be a Mercedes mechanic.

Here are some breakdowns of where the money will go.

  • £5 can support a working guide dog for a day
  • £25 can buy a white harness, the iconic symbol of a fully qualified guide dog
  • £95 can buy a Training School Kit for a guide dog trainer who teach pups the specialist skills they will need to become a qualified guide dog.
  • £140 can buy a Starter Kit for a new guide dog owner containing everything they need to start a life with their new guide dog. 
Thank you so much for your donation, mum will be smiling down at you.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss. We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Our mother, Shirley, was taken ill early in January. After being taken into hospital with mild COVID symptoms it was discovered after testing and scanning that she had advanced stage colorectal cancer. Because of the progression of the disease no treatment was available. Eventually she was moved to Braintree Nursing home where we could see her. She passed away late on Wednesday 3rd February and verified on early hours of 4th.

Our mother had many friends from the school where she worked for over 26 years to all the clubs she belonged to. She always kept herself fit and busy and will be missed by many.

Shirley continued supporting the a Great Ormond Street Hospital charity since her grandson, Tomas, became ill. So in memory of Shirley and her late grandsons Tomas, Aaron and Joshua please kindly donate to GOSH.

Thank you.



Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.
title: Andrew's page

charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
Great Ormond Street Hospital Childrens Charity (GOSH Charity) and McColls, the leading neighbourhood retailer, are delighted to announce a brand-new charity partnership that aims to raise £1million over the next three years.

Seriously ill children from across the UK travel to Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) for specialist treatment for rare and complex conditions.

The money raised by McColls will help fund GOSH Charitys vital parent accommodation service, supporting the refurbishment of 'McColl's House', which brings families closer together when a child is receiving treatment.

By partnering with GOSH Charity, McColls colleagues and customers will support families at the heart of their communities, right across the UK.

pageSummaryWhat: I am doing the walk 62 miles in March challenge
pageSummaryWhy: GOSH have provided excellent care for Laurie
story:
We are doing the walk 62 miles in March challenge for Great Ormond Street Hospital.

Laurie has a rare medical condition affecting her lungs, digestive system, bones and joints.GOSH have provided excellent care and assisted in treatment plans for Laurie since the age of 6months old. Her condition is monitored by GOSH and because of the rarity of her condition she will always be a patient at GOSH.


The charity supports the hospital and its patients by providing funding for rebuilding and refurbishment, child and family support, research and medical equipment. 

So to say thank you to them for everything they've done,we want to help raise a few pennies so we’ve set ourselves a challenge to walk 62 miles in March.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
pageSummary: 310000 because Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
pageSummaryWhy: Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: I am raising money because their wonderful staff helped Mum remain at home
pageSummaryWhy: their wonderful staff helped Mum remain at home
story:
Our Solihull Hospice has been caring for local people since 1965.

Its a warm and welcoming place where we give expert care to people with a terminal illness, and their loved ones, every day of the year. 

Our hospice team includes doctors, nurses, physiotherapists, social workers and many more, and is supported by over 200 volunteers  who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.

We have a 24-bed in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night, and stay with their loved ones if they wish.

Our out-patient unit offers clinics, therapies and group sessions  and freshly cooked lunches made by our chefs. We also support carers and families, including children, with practical advice, counselling and bereavement support groups.

We need to raise £9,600 per day to run the hospice, so every penny counts. Thank you for helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Solihull get the care and support they need.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
We've been caring for people with serious illnesses in Barnet, Brent, Camden, Enfield, Haringey and Islington for more than 60 years, now.

Every single day at the hospice is an extraordinary day. And every moment is precious. Our hospice nurses, doctors and therapists provide the best possible care for people with serious illnesses, and offer vital emotional support for them and their families. 

The hospice is a warm, welcoming place where loved ones can be together in peaceful surroundings and in as much comfort as possible. Whether it's for one day or several weeks, the time people spend at the hospice is precious, and is cherished by them and their families.

Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in North London get the care and support they need.

"When I was admitted, I was confined to a wheelchair, in constant pain. Now I walk between five and seven miles a day. You can see how good Marie Curie is in that I walk" - Matthew

eventName: Matt’s Malin to Mizen 600km challenge run
pageSummary: Raising money because lockdown does strange things to people!
pageSummaryWhy: lockdown does strange things to people!
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I'm attempting to run the length of Ireland in February 2021 to raise some funds for Marie Curie, who provide invaluable support to people living with terminal illness and their families.

The distance from Malin Head in Co.Donegal to Mizen Head in Co. Cork is approximately 600km. I aim to cover this by running / walking at least 21km on average per day, every day for 28 days. Due to current lockdown restrictions, I will be doing this distance around the streets and trails of beautiful Belfast.

I'm running in memory of my beloved mum Norma, whom we lost suddenly to cancer in 2016, also my uncles "George" Elliot, Steven Vernon, Tony Griffiths and aunt Margaret Griffiths as well as friends Ash Reynolds and Matt Currie who have been taken recently by various forms of this grim illness.

Every step will be in their honour.

I'm certain any donation you can afford would be greatly appreciated by the patients you will be supporting.


The challenge was originally posed by the awesome One Element outdoor fitness community. Our Belfast club is competing against and contributing to a total distance covered by clubs across the UK. How far will we get??!! Circumnavigation of the planet is on the cards for sure!

Thanks again for taking time to read this far!

G'wan ya good thing!

pageSummary: This is to make donations because of the support they gave us during Mam's illness
pageSummaryWhy: of the support they gave us during Mam's illness
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

We have set this up in lieu of flowers to remember our mother, Ann Flint, who passed away on Friday 19 February after fighting cancer. Marie Curie gave us lots of support in her final months and we'd like to support them in return.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: I am trying to squat 3000 times in March because They are an amazing organisation, full of kindness
pageSummaryWhat: I am trying to squat 3000 times in March
pageSummaryWhy: They are an amazing organisation, full of kindness
story:
It's been nearly 10 years since we lost dad (that always sounds so careless!), and memories are fading about that really difficult time.... But one thing I won't ever forget was the kindness and compassion from the Marie Curie nurses that helped us through dad's last few nights. 

It would have been Dad's birthday in March and I'm taking part in the Marie Curie Facebook challenge of 3000 squats in March to raise both awareness and funds.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
For Marie Curie our Great Daffodil Appeal month of March is normally full of some wonderful fundraising & fabulous support and this year we need your help more than ever before. With no collections in supermarkets, daffodil pins in shops & businesses or face to face events, we really do need you to help us reach all corners of our communities, to give everyone the chance to donate and get their virtual daffodil. Our nurses have never been busier as all health care professionals strive to keep patients at home for their care. Please donate to our virtual collection so that we can continue to help care for our patients and support their families through such a difficult & emotional time.

pageSummaryWhy: Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
eventName: Donate in Michael Charles Morris's memory. Raise money for RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution.
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.
title: Donate in Michael Charles Morris's memory. Raise money for RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution.
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA

Name: Donate in Michael Charles Morris's memory. Raise money for RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

story:
Hi!

Some of Hydenlyne office staff are entering Royal Parks Half Marathon on Sunday 11 April 2021 in aid of charity WWF - World Wildlife Foundation, a charity close to our hearts.

Sadly due to Covid-19 the event cannot be held in the Royal Parks but will instead be ran individually in a green or outdoor space close to the home of each entrant.

This does give us the opportunity to involve others though, and we welcome anyone to get involved be it consultants, clients or partners. Anyone who want to join us on the day, no matter how many miles, ran, walked or jogged and post their pictures or run trackers to help us raise money for such a good cause.

For more information or to get involved please get in touch: enquiries@hydenlyne.com !

Thank you for reading our page. Any donations are greatly appreciated, especially during these hard times.

All money donated on this platform goes directly to WWF. More info below regarding WWF.

Many thanks,
Hydenlyne

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
pageSummary: Oliver is going to take part in the mad March mile because He wants to help children to keep safe
pageSummaryWhat: Oliver is going to take part in the mad March mile
pageSummaryWhy: He wants to help children to keep safe
story:
Oliver has chosen to walk/scoot/cycle/run a mile a day as part of the mad March mile because he wanted to set himself a challenge and raise money for children who have been affected by coronavirus. He hopes everyone will support him so he can help lots of other children!

I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

eventName: Practising Chairwork: Basics and Beyond - Fundraising
story:
Chairwork is raising funds for Doctors Without Borders via our free online training course 'Practising Chairwork: Basics and Beyond'.

If you enjoyed our training, or would like to support our fundraising, please consider making a donation to one our nominated charities. 100% donations go directly to the charity you choose. 

About this charity: 

Doctors Without Borders provides medical assistance to people affected by conflict, epidemics, disasters, or exclusion from healthcare. Our teams are made up of tens of thousands of health professionals, logistic and administrative staff - most of them hired locally. Our actions are guided by medical ethics and the principles of impartiality, independence and neutrality.

charity.description: Malaria No More UK mobilises governments, influencers, businesses and the public to end deaths from malaria and wipe out the disease for good. Our mission is to catalyse and inspire the global partnerships, leadership and financing to make malaria no more in a generation.
charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story:
據估計，在2019年，全世界有409,000人死於瘧疾，這是一種可預防的疾病，罹患者大多數是五歲以下兒童和孕婦（來源：世界衛生組織）。

2021年是全球運動中使我們的世界沒有瘧疾的至關重要的一年。今年6月，英聯邦政府首腦會議與至關重要的吉佳利瘧疾及被忽視的熱帶疾病首腦會議，將會在盧安達舉行。此高峰會標記著一個歷史性時刻，它將團結全球領導人，並將重點放在採取新行動對付瘧疾的重要性上。我們需要更多的行動、更多的創新、更多的資金以及更多的政治領導才能戰勝瘧疾，並在這個新的全球衛生格局中更強大。

在Rentokil Initial，同事們都參加了9,000公里的吉佳利賽跑（我們的總部和盧安達首都吉佳利距離9,000公里），包括來自美國、澳洲、亞洲、歐洲、中東、加勒比、非洲、人力資源、資訊、財務金融、併購及法律的團隊。通過結合同事們散步、跑步或騎自行車的努力，每個團隊將“達到”與吉佳利的距離。這是我們在全球努力籌集資金並表示對這一重要事業的支持。一切從2月15日星期一開始，一直到4月25日聯合國世界瘧疾日。

Andy Ransom(Rentokil Initial的首席執行官)：「作為’’瘧疾不再''團隊的驕傲贊助人，我邀請在Rentokil Initial的同事以及朋友、家人和他們的同事一起參與到吉佳利賽跑中。這樣做，在這樣的關鍵時刻幫助’’瘧疾不再’’籌集了極其重要的資金。我們的慈善基金Rentokil Initial Cares，希望可以達成募集£100,000的目標。」

只要一起努力，我們可以在一個世代的時間內實現零瘧疾的世界。

非常歡迎也感謝你們的支持。

In 2019 it is estimated that 409,000 people around the world died from malaria - a preventable disease - the majority being children under five and pregnant women (source: WHO). 

2021 is a vital year in the global campaign to make our world one without malaria. This coming June, the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and the vitally important Kigali Summit on malaria and neglected tropical diseases will take place in Rwanda. The summit marks a historic moment that will unite global leaders and put a spotlight on the importance of renewed action in fighting malaria. We need more action, more innovation, more funding and more political leadership to defeat malaria and move forward stronger in this new global health landscape.

Across Rentokil Initial, colleagues are taking part in a 9,000km Race to Kigali (the distance between our HQ and Kigali, Rwanda), including teams from America, Australia, Asia, Europe, the Middle East, Caribbean, Africa, HR, IT, Finance, M&A and Legal. By combining the efforts of colleagues walking, running or cycling, each team will ‘reach’ the distance to Kigali. This is our global effort to raise funds and show our support for this vital cause. It all starts on Monday 15 February through to the UN’s World Malaria Day on 25 April.

Andy Ransom: "As a proud patron of Malaria No More UK, I am asking my colleagues at Rentokil Initial, as well as friends, family and associates to get involved in the Race to Kigali. In doing so, helping raise incredibly important funding for Malaria No More UK at such a critical time. Rentokil Initial Cares, our charitable fund, will match every £1 raised up to £100,000.” 

 Together we can achieve a Zero Malaria world within a generation.

Please show your support.

charity.name: MALARIA NO MORE UK
story: Kigali in Rwanda is where Malaria No More will be meeting the Commonwealth Heads of Government in June 2021 to try and secure vital funding. Our challenge: Cover the distance – 9,000km – working together in teams and aim to raise up to £100,000 in sponsorship and RI Cares donations. Demonstrating that we know the importance of Malaria prevention. Example: Teams of up to 20 people (x5km per day per person) = 100km per day 90 days = 9,000km Each colleague to walk, ride, run, swim, row…. 5km per day (on average over a week): c. 6,500 steps per day. c. 20-30mins on an exercise bike c. 40-60mins walking around customer sites

story:
I am going to run 2km for WaterAid because I keep seeing the adverts on tv and want to help people have  clean water.

I’m doing my run around Brockley’s Walk (2 1/2 laps) on Saturday 20th February and I’ve been practicing during half term.

Thank you very much.

Love Molly  x



Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.
